<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1664,1914]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Material: the only specimen known (male 
<typeStatus box="[645,749,1664,1690]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">holotype</typeStatus>
) is deposited at Harvard. In spite of the attempts to borrow the material, neither the specimen nor photographs were available for study.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,1664,1914]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Discussion and diagnosis. This species is known from one male imago from 
<collectingCountry box="[1171,1269,1738,1764]" name="Ecuador" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(Durar). The original description and figures are inadequate to species characterization but clearly indicate that this species belongs to 
<taxonomicName box="[283,392,1814,1839]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[283,392,1814,1839]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Tortopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as is recovered in the phylogenetic tree (
<figureCitation box="[893,986,1813,1839]" captionStart="FIGURE 1. A" captionStartId="4.[151,256,1731,1755]" captionTargetBox="[207,1379,197,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[207,1380,197,1701]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. A, strict consensus of 234 shortest trees obtained with the complete data set (58 steps, Ci = 81, Ri = 93); B, strict consensus of 3 shortest trees obtained with the reduced data set (58 steps, Ci = 81, Ri = 92). Values near nodes indicate group support (frequency difference / absolute Bremer Support / relative BS). Black circles indicate unique apomorphies, white circles indicate parallelism or reversal, the small numbers above and below these marks are character and state numbers respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195432/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Fig. 
<number box="[949,960,1813,1839]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="1.0">1</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). The main feature used to assign the species to 
<taxonomicName box="[277,384,1851,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Tortopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[277,384,1851,1876]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Tortopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the form of the penes, widely separated from each other from their bases. Fore wing length is reported to be 
<quantity box="[428,555,1888,1914]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10â€“12 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Banks" box="[570,715,1888,1914]" pageId="24" pageNumber="34" refString="Banks, N. (1918) New neuropteroid insects. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 62 (1), 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="1918">
Banks 
<number box="[652,715,1888,1914]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" value="1918.0">1918</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
